## Why?
With the recent **destroying** of Jarred Summer by Andrew Kelly, it's of course the question: Will this hit other zig projects?
How would Andrew react to the Cubyz codebase? Are we in the line for the next "worst zig codebase"?

## How?

First we need to lay down why we could be targeted. What are we doing different than its normally done in Zig projects?

### Memory managment:
One of the greatest points of Zig so much that they point it out on their main website page is: 
> No hidden memory allocations.

In Cubyz the memory managment goes as follows:
- you are allocationg something which should then be handeld by the caller? -> allocator on function signature.
- you are not doing that? -> use one of the global set allocators in `main.zig`

While maybe not the worst handeling of memory managment, one thing comes out of here which is not quite liked by Andrew.

### Global variables
Here it's not even a question if Andrew would see our usage of global Variables bad. 
Here is the reply of Andrew to a comment from Cubyz main developer Quantum about [carrying dependencies](https://ziggit.dev/t/carrying-dependencies/16215/6)
>I respect that you came to this opinion by maintaining a large codebase over a long period of time. However, I have done the same and arrived at the opposite conclusion: globals make code significantly harder to read, and particularly difficult to refactor. Speaking from experience, when a collaborator uses global variables, it’s extremely frustrating to edit their code with any sort of confidence.

Are we now screwed? I don't think so. This feels like a disagreement but not so much that it could let to monthly meetings about how to make our code better.

### Handeling of Errors
I think here it's going back to the memory managment problem. In Cubyz code you can often find 
```zig
allocation catch unreachable
```
This is something I myself don't like, but we would have to copy the entire std to get this gone, as our `NeverFailingAllocator` as the name implies never fails. What does that mean? If you don't have enough memory? We crash. Simple as that. Is that a great strategy? Not really. Even for a game you don't really want to crash just because the user doens't have enough memory. But what would that for the project mean when you need to handle all memory erros? I think for this Quantum can explain that better. So read the [ziggit Cubyz](https://ziggit.dev/t/cubyz-a-voxel-game-written-in-zig/8406) post where this is explained!

### Tab vs spaces
This is probably the biggest grievance that we have with zig. This will probably be never a point of Andrew against us, but us against Andrew (and we are not the only ones). Zig has since long taken a great stance in the tabs vs spaces war. In Cubyz we use tabs. In Zig 4 spaces are used. Here it should end, but it doesn't. Tabs are a compile error in zig comments. yes. You heard right. A compile error. While we can survive this, if this is made worse through other thngs in the compiler I don't know what we would do.

## When?
So when will Cubyz be the next Bun in Andew Kellys mind? 
My opinion: probably (hopefully) never. While I can see that we are not the best zig representation, we still are pretty "ziggy" in my opinion.

So in conclusion: I just needed a reason to try write a blog post. Is this post serious? Not really.

For everyone out there: Just enable your asserts in prod and you may be safe from Andrews rath.

Bye!

-- Wunka
